[2] Saudi Arabia, 7 new cases, 2 deaths 19 Apr 2014
Date: Sat 19 Apr 2014
Source: Saudi MOH website [in Arabic, machine trans., edited]
http://www.moh.gov.sa/CoronaNew/PressReleases/Pages/mediastatemenet-2014-04-19-001.aspx


MOH: Confirmation of 7 new MERS-CoV infections in Jeddah
--------------------------------------------------------
In the context of the work of epidemiological investigation and ongoing follow-up carried out by the Ministry of Health for the MERS-CoV, the MOH announces the registration of 7 new cases of the virus in Jeddah.

The 1st is a 64-year-old male resident who died.

The 2nd is a 44-year-old male resident who also died.

The 3rd is a 62-year-old citizen and the 4th is a 47-year-old citizen, both of whom are being treated in intensive care.

The 5th is a 52-year-old male citizen in stable condition.

The 6th and 7th are both 54 years old, and both are working in the health field, and both are asymptomatic.

170 samples have been checked during this period (since the last mention) and all were negative except the 7 mentioned above.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The above reports of 7 new laboratory confirmed cases including 2 deaths brings the total number of laboratory confirmed cases of MERS-CoV infection in Saudi Arabia to 231 including 76 deaths. Of note, 2 of the newly confirmed cases are asymptomatic healthcare workers, 1 is in stable condition, 2 are seriously ill being treated in intensive care, and 2 died.

At present there have been a total of 50 laboratory confirmed cases of MERS-CoV infection reported from Jeddah since mid-March 2014, of whom 9 (18 percent) have died, 8 (16 percent) are seriously ill in intensive care, 12 (24 percent) are in stable condition, 1 (2 percent) was reported as "recovered" and 20 (40 percent) were asymptomatic (presumably diagnosed as part of contact tracing). 18 (36 percent) of the MERS-CoV infected individuals in this outbreak are in health care workers.

Sofian Ragab from the IDPHR group (Infectious Disease Public Health Research group), <sofian@idph-research.org>, submitted a link to a map showing the MERS-CoV distribution of cases in Saudi Arabia as of 18 Apr 2014. This map can be found at http://goo.gl/9TKN19. - Mod.MPP]

