[4] Global overview - ECDC 17 Apr 2014
Date: Thu 17 Apr 2014
Source: ECDC Communicable Disease Threats Report (CDTR) [edited]
http://www.ecdc.europa.eu/en/publications/Publications/communicable-disease-threats-report-19-april-2014.pdf


Since April 2012, 275 laboratory-confirmed cases, including 98 deaths, of acute respiratory disease caused by Middle East respiratory syndrome coronavirus (MERS-CoV), have been reported by national health authorities. To date, all cases have either occurred in the Middle East, have had direct links to a primary case infected in the Middle East, or have returned from this area. The source of the virus remains unknown but the pattern of transmission points towards an animal reservoir in the Middle East, from which humans sporadically become infected through zoonotic transmission. Human-to-human transmission to close contacts and in hospital settings has occurred, but there is no evidence of sustained transmission among humans. MERS-CoV is genetically distinct from the coronavirus that caused the SARS outbreak.

Since the previous CDTR, 44 new cases have been reported in the Middle East. 30 cases have been reported from Saudi Arabia including 5 deaths and 14 cases, including one death, from the United Arab Emirates. In addition, the Philippines reported one case in a person recently returned from the United Arab Emirates. Malaysia also reported a case that later died, in a traveller recently returned from Saudi Arabia.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Since the ECDC report was published on 18 Apr 2014 there have been additional cases reported from Saudi Arabia as well as the UAE and Greece, with the total number of laboratory confirmed cases approaching 300. With the major increase in reports of contact associated cases of MERS-CoV infection, the numbers are growing significantly as the case fatality rate (CFR) is dropping (see section [2] above showing the CFR in the Jeddah outbreak is 18 percent, with 40 percent of the reported MERS-CoV infected individuals found to be asymptomatic infections).

There has been additional media and social media chatter telling of individuals identified as suspected cases travelling from the Middle East to other countries, as well as an Arabic language media report mentioning a suspected case in Jordan, pending confirmation (http://www.jordanzad.com/index.php?page=article&id=156730, in Arabic). Clearly there is now a heightened awareness for MERS-CoV with the marked increase in reported laboratory confirmations in the past few weeks (and days). Perhaps the silver lining of this cloud will be an increase in epidemiologic investigations including case control studies to further define risk factors for disease transmission and the as yet elusive "proof" of the animal reservoir that serves as the nidus of infection for the species jump of this virus to human infections. - Mod.MPP]
